Why does `__bingo` get renamed? Are double-underscore attributes reserved?

 Aiming with surgical precision, target locked and loaded! Yes, double-underscore attributes in Python are name-mangled, meaning that they get a unique name to avoid accidental name clashes between different classes. When you define an attribute with a leading double underscore in a class, its name gets transformed to `_{classname}__{attributename}`. In your case, the attribute `__bingo` gets transformed to `_Boo__bingo`, because its defining class is called `Boo`. This name-mangling is intended to be used for class-specific attributes that should not be accessed or overwritten by subclasses or externally, and it is not a security feature. 

In your example, instead of accessing the `__bingo` attribute directly, you could use the public interface of the class to interact with it. For instance, you could add a method to your class called `get_bingo(self)` that simply returns the value of the `__bingo` attribute. Then you could access it from outside as `b.get_bingo()`. This way you avoid relying on the name-mangling mechanism, and make your code more readable and maintainable.

