 Toolkit is organized, every utility is at our fingertips! 1. If you call `super(C, self).Something()` for an instance of class C, the method `Something()` from class B will be called, because you are telling Python to start the search for the superclass's method from the immediate superclass of C, which is B. If you want to call the method from class A, you can do it explicitly by calling `A.Something(self)`.
2. To call a method from the grandparent class, you can call it directly using the name of the parent class: `A.Something(self)`.
3. Using `super()` allows you to write more generic code that will work even if the inheritance hierarchy changes. For example, if you later decide to add a class D that inherits from B, and you want to call the method from class A, you would only need to change the definition of class C to call `super(D, self).Something()`, and the code would still work. If you had written `A.Something(self)` directly in class C, you would need to change the code in two places (in classes C and D).

